<!-- wp:heading -->
<h2><a></a><a target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener"></a>6. Consider certain foods and herbs</h2>
<!-- /wp:heading -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>There are several foods that you may wish to include in your diet to combat water retention.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>The following foods and herbs are often recommended by alternative practitioners to drop water weight (<a rel="noreferrer noopener" href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/22890173" target="_blank">20Trusted Source</a>,&nbsp;<a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/35168030/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">21Trusted Source</a>,&nbsp;<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC5698599/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">22Trusted Source</a>,&nbsp;<a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/33507846/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">23Trusted Source</a>,&nbsp;<a href="https://www.researchgate.net/publication/280562395_Therapeutic_and_pharmacological_potential_of_Foeniculum_vulgare_Mill_A_review" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">24</a>,&nbsp;<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC5009491/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">25Trusted Source</a>):</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:list -->
<ul><li><a href="https://www.healthline.com/nutrition/corn-silk">corn silk</a></li><li><a href="https://www.healthline.com/nutrition/horsetail">horsetail</a></li><li><a href="https://www.healthline.com/nutrition/parsley-benefits">parsley</a></li><li><a href="https://www.healthline.com/nutrition/hibiscus-tea-benefits">hibiscus</a></li><li><a href="https://www.healthline.com/nutrition/fennel-and-fennel-seed-benefits">fennel</a></li><li><a href="https://www.healthline.com/nutrition/stinging-nettle">nettle</a></li></ul>
<!-- /wp:list -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>However, keep in mind that research on the&nbsp;<a href="https://www.healthline.com/health/natural-diuretics">diuretic</a>&nbsp;properties of these herbal ingredients is currently limited to test-tube and animal studies.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>Additionally, though bloating is usually not caused by water retention, you may also wish to limit or temporarily remove&nbsp;<a href="https://www.healthline.com/nutrition/13-foods-that-cause-bloating">foods that may cause bloating</a>.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>These include highly processed foods, foods with lots of fiber, and sometimes beans or dairy. You can also try sticking to&nbsp;<a href="https://www.healthline.com/nutrition/fodmaps-101">low FODMAP foods</a>&nbsp;for a while to see if that helps.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:quote -->
<blockquote class="wp-block-quote"><p><strong>SUMMARY</strong></p><p>Certain foods and herbs can act as diuretics and reduce water retention. Combine them with easily digestible foods that don’t cause bloating or intolerances.</p></blockquote>
<!-- /wp:quote -->

<!-- wp:heading -->
<h2><a></a><a target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener"></a>7. Cut carbs</h2>
<!-- /wp:heading -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>Cutting&nbsp;<a href="https://www.healthline.com/nutrition/good-carbs-bad-carbs">carbs</a>&nbsp;is a common strategy to quickly drop excess water. Carbs are stored in the muscles and liver as glycogen, but glycogen also pulls water inside along with it.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>For every gram of glycogen you store, 3–4 grams (0.11–0.14 ounces) of water may be stored with it. This explains why people experience immediate weight loss when switching to a&nbsp;<a href="https://www.healthline.com/nutrition/low-carb-diet-meal-plan-and-menu">low carb diet</a>, which reduces glycogen stores (<a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/25911631/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">26Trusted Source</a>).</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>Carbs also lead to a rise in the hormone insulin, which can increase sodium retention and reabsorption of water in the kidneys (<a href="https://www.frontiersin.org/articles/10.3389/fcell.2020.00519/full" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">27</a>).</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>Low carb diets lead to a drop in insulin levels, which could lead to a loss of sodium and water from the kidneys.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>Try altering your&nbsp;<a href="https://www.healthline.com/nutrition/how-many-carbs-per-day-to-lose-weight">carb intake</a>&nbsp;and see what works best for you.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:quote -->
<blockquote class="wp-block-quote"><p><strong>SUMMARY</strong></p><p>A low carb diet can cause a rapid decrease in water weight because of reduced glycogen stores and lower insulin levels.</p></blockquote>
<!-- /wp:quote -->

<!-- wp:heading -->
<h2><a></a><a target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener"></a>8. Take caffeine supplements or drink tea and coffee</h2>
<!-- /wp:heading -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>Caffeine and beverages that contain caffeine, such as&nbsp;<a href="https://www.healthline.com/nutrition/top-evidence-based-health-benefits-of-coffee">coffee</a>&nbsp;and tea, have diuretic effects and may help reduce water weight.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>It has been shown to increase short-term urine output and decrease water weight slightly (<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC5563313/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">28Trusted Source</a>,&nbsp;<a href="https://medlineplus.gov/caffeine.html" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">29</a>).</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>This may vary depending on the amount of&nbsp;<a href="https://www.healthline.com/nutrition/what-is-caffeine">caffeine</a>&nbsp;that is consumed.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>For instance, one small study found that drinking about 537 milligrams (mg) of caffeine, or approximately 6 cups of coffee, significantly increased urine production. On the other hand, drinking 269 mg of caffeine, or around 3 cups of coffee, had no effect on fluid balance (<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC5563313/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">28Trusted Source</a>).</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>Furthermore, even though caffeine may have a mild diuretic effect, other research suggests that it doesn’t lead to dehydration in habitual consumers (<a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/24416202/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">30Trusted Source</a>).</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:quote -->
<blockquote class="wp-block-quote"><p><strong>SUMMARY</strong></p><p>Some research suggests that caffeine from coffee, tea, or caffeine supplements may help you drop excess water. However, more studies are needed.</p></blockquote>
<!-- /wp:quote -->

<!-- wp:heading -->
<h2><a>The bottom line</a></h2>
<!-- /wp:heading -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>If your water retention problem persists, seems severe, or increases suddenly, it’s always best to seek medical attention.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>In some cases, excess water retention can be caused by a serious medical condition.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>At the end of the day, the best way to combat excess water weight is to identify and treat the cause.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>This may include excess salt intake, lack of electrolytes, inactivity, excess stress, or the regular consumption of&nbsp;<a href="https://www.healthline.com/nutrition/junk-food-vs-healthy-food">processed foods</a>.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>Some of these are also among the main causes linked to poor health and disease, which may be even bigger reasons to avoid them.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->
